{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d4e589e6-89a0-4265-ba30-ff7932778a07","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. They contain the stack trace, signal info, and loaded images.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a GUI view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file appears at `/tmp/core.<pid>` and can be inspected with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /tmp/core.12345\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the fastest path to a diagnosis without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c6e3517-62aa-4e24-9c16-0da973b57803","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":323,"requestId":"2C40:26FA86:16B57D0:1997007:69F94C8A"},"id":"bb006f30-9d59-47bb-9ba8-280a9f801fb3","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:49:10.703Z","parentId":"d4458112-bdee-4993-9b55-d86bd96df7f0"}
